{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628927"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:02:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:02:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17250"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17250"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9940"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69846"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9940"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17250"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55302"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"6878"},{"type":"tags","id":"9998"},{"type":"tags","id":"10476"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23303"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23444"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69846"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESaliva is produced by three pairs of major salivary glands: the parotid, submandibular, and sublingual glands. The composition and volume of saliva are tightly regulated.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the process of saliva production?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Active calcium transport drives water secretion","Direct hormonal control regulates protein secretion","Osmotic gradient from sodium chloride transport drives fluid secretion","Passive diffusion of proteins determines saliva composition","Simple filtration from blood produces saliva"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eosmotic gradients created by sodium chloride transport\u003C/strong\u003E. Acinar cells actively transport sodium chloride into the interstitial space, creating an osmotic gradient that draws water through water channels. This produces the primary secretion which is then modified in the ducts.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive calcium transport drives water secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - While calcium signaling is important for cellular regulation, it does not directly drive water movement\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect hormonal control regulates protein secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Protein secretion is primarily controlled by autonomic nerves, not hormones\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive diffusion of proteins determines saliva composition\u003C/strong\u003E - Proteins are actively secreted by exocytosis\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple filtration from blood produces saliva\u003C/strong\u003E - Saliva is produced by active secretory processes, not by filtration\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe final composition of saliva results from both fluid secretion driven by osmotic gradients and regulated protein secretion. The process is controlled by both parasympathetic (primarily fluid) and sympathetic (primarily protein) neural inputs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Saliva production involves both fluid secretion from serous cells and protein/mucus secretion from mucous cells.","Parasympathetic stimulation primarily controls fluid secretion while sympathetic stimulation controls protein secretion.","Active transport of sodium chloride creates osmotic gradients that drive water movement into salivary ducts."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Asbury, C., Rieke, F., Hille, B., Bothwell, M., \u0026 Tuthill, J. (2023) Physiology. Simple Book Publishing. https://uw.pressbooks.pub/physiology/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55302"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17250"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55302"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T20:54:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T20:55:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9940"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69846"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nul